Czech discovery: a substance that also works in ‘stitched’ HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds to prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the organism.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works in the viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact prevails against the disadvantage that the compound does not act as strongly on common virus variants as one of the already existing drugs.
The disease AIDS can not yet be cured.
However, the patient can prolong the drug composition and prevent the proliferation of HIV viruses in the body.
However, your intake is accompanied by a number of side effects.
In addition, incomplete suppression of viral proliferation results in the development of resistant viruses, against which drugs are no longer effective.
The work of the experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, from VSCHT (Chemical-Technological University) Prague and from the University of Heidelberg opens the way to dealing with virus resistance.
They have shown that the substances referred to as metalocarborane act on the protein that is responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
The metalocarboranes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block viral proliferation in a different way than all drugs used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists arrive at new ‘improved’ compounds prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the viral protein.
The metalocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-variate cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Homethick and persistent virus
HIV protease is the protein of the HIV virus, which is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus cleavage caused by the HIV protease, there would be no mature infectious virus particles.
When we turn off the HIV protease, we also turn off the proliferation of the virus in the patient’s body, the scientists explain in the press report published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the paper published in the Journal of Medical Chemistry, the scientists describe whole series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which is then systematically further changed.
A little weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances against HIV protease was tested in the test tube, also against their resistant (resistant) variants obtained by HIV-infected patients.
The effect of the metalocarborane on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as in the medicinal products used clinically, but it does not lose its effect on the resistance variants against which the medicinal products used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action as well as its other properties, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical designs, makes the metalocarboranes interesting compounds for further research on the development of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlina Rezacova, head of the Laboratory of Structural Biology of the Institutes of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy.
