New vaccination
Vaccines free for August children
From January, children can be vaccinated for free against pneumococcal disease, which was born on August 2 last year and later.
The condition is that they have not yet received a vaccine dose.
Anyone who has already started the vaccination in the past year or earlier must also pay for further repeat vaccination themselves.
The first vaccination dose must be given between the 3rd and 5th months of the child’s life.
Last year, a quarter of families had their children vaccinated against pneumococcal disease.
The parents paid 1,600 kroner and more for a dose.
Four doses are required for the vaccination of the youngest children.
Overall, the experts estimate that health insurance companies spend 300,000 to 450,000 kroner per year on vaccine doses.
However, you will save on the treatment that the children would need without vaccination.
So far, the state has spent about 500,000 per year on all children’s land vaccinations.
The mandatory vaccination was introduced with the so-called Janota package.
Pneumococci cause middle ear inflammation, but also severe infections including brain inflammation and blood poisoning.
Pneumococcal infections cause up to 28 children up to 10 years of age after being examined in hospitals per year.
Outside the Czech Republic, the compulsory vaccination of children against pneumococcal disease was introduced in about 40 countries.
Will the vaccination be mandatory?
At the same time, it is said that this vaccination could be mandatory in the future.
As of January, it is to be paid by the insurance companies and voluntary.
That the mandatory vaccination would be better, mentioned, for example, the head of the citizens' association Nahlas, Rudolf Kalovsky.
His association has long been promoting pneumococcal vaccination.
The experts at the international conference in which our association was involved were not very satisfied that we had voluntary vaccination.
That's not quite ideal.
On the other hand, we are glad that we have managed to achieve at least that.
I think that's the way we have to go now, Kalovsky said.
However, the Ministry of Health does not want to change the vaccination procedure against pneumococcal cancer.
At this moment we are not considering this at all, said his spokesman Vlastimil Sesen.
The voluntary vaccination has its drawbacks, doctors claim.
Hana Cabrnochova, the chairman of the medical community of practical pediatricians, admits that a voluntary vaccination has its drawbacks.
If all children were vaccinated, then one might think about reducing the number of repeat vaccinations "In a situation where the vaccine is so expensive, we understand the political decision that this vaccination was started as a voluntary one," says Cabrnochova.
Experts expect more than 80 percent of parents to vaccinate their infants against pneumococcal disease from next year.
Vaccination against pneumococcal disease is also ground-breaking in that it is the first area vaccination paid by health insurance companies and not by the state.
The insurance companies should spend the money on prevention, thus saving them for further treatment, explains Cabrnochova.
Doctors have to buy the vaccines themselves.
However, this involves a concern of the practical pediatricians, which concerns the purchase of the vaccines.
According to the original plan, the vaccines should be purchased by the insurance companies and the doctors then receive them on the same route as other vaccines issued by the state to them.
Some MPs, however, feared that the insurance companies could "execute the money from health insurance".
