Shanghai will soon be "as old -- but not as rich -- as the industrialized countries, like Japan and Sweden," she said.
A step-by-step relaxation
Anchored in the country’s constitution in 1978, China’s one-child policy may well be the most controversial provision introduced by the ruling Communist Party to this day.
Couples who violate this policy must expect huge fines -- up to their triple annual salary in some regions -- and discrimination at their workplace.
Chinese state officials have attributed it to this policy that the critical use of natural land resources could be avoided, whereas human rights defenders have condemned abuses in the enforcement of the policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women who had already had a child to drive off.
Many couples had also had sex-selective abortions performed, creating an unnaturally high relationship between men and women.
In recent years, government representatives for the population have gradually weakened their stance on one-child policies.
In 2004, they approved more exceptions to the rule -- including city dwellers, members of ethnic minorities, and cases where both husband and wife were single children -- and in 2007 the tone of many hard slogans was softened.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute of Population Research at the University of Beijing, said government officials have recently even discussed more radical changes, for example, allowing couples to have two children, where a partner is a single child.
Shanghai became the first Chinese city in July to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births.
Posters that taught families to have only one child were replaced almost overnight by guidelines that describe in detail who is eligible for a second child and how to apply for approval.
