The Cradle of Dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: The two-meter-long and 1.50-meter-sized animal ran on two powerful hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would have been nothing special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body features, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the journal Science on Thursday.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in present-day New Mexico, which was then in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pang<0xC3><0xA4>a on the equator.
Tawa opens a new window to the early evolution of the dinosaurs, Nesbitt says.
He shows us a lot about the relationship, the spread and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began digging at the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We have sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the Trias, team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History reports.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as a new species.
In the course of the excavation, they carried together the remains of a total of five individuals.
Fund confirms theories about Dino's early history
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it is an extraordinary finding: "Dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare, usually only single fragments can be found."
Other dinosaur experts don’t necessarily share the enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of the dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current doctrine, the dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these primordial dinosaurs is mostly controversial.
For example, the experts debate when the lizards split into their three main lines of development: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the Tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the four-legged sauropods known as the "long-necked" and their relatives, and the plant-eating ornithophagus (Vogelosaia) are among the species's.
After the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropod.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found clues about air bags, as they also have the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the airbags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
At Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were apparently also partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with airbags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of giant sauropods later also had airbags and lightweight construction bones, probably the common ancestor of both groups had already produced this useful innovation.
At least three migration waves to North America
Because the most primitive known dinosaurs lived in South America, the researchers conclude that the lizards first appeared there.
Accordingly, the three development lines separated early on and spread from South America across all continents, which at that time formed a single land mass as the supercontinent Pang<0xC3><0xA4>a.
The team, together with Tawa hallae, found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related, theropods.
The three cannot be descended from a common immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three migration waves to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says paleontologist Martin Sander.
In his opinion, a distorted picture could emerge, because in South America, just a particularly large number of primitive dinosaur fossils have been preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to be found.
As the dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare sideline of the reptile tribe to the dominant terrestrial vertebrates of the Middle Ages, it is still mysterious.
During the Triassic period, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today’s crocodiles and the fly-acids and with numerous other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassics, the dinosaurs spread all over the world and developed many new species, while their relatives died out on the border from the Triassic to the Jurassic.
Success story did not last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass death that the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so that they could beat the competition out of the field.
In any case, the success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact helped a group of animals to bloom, which had also developed in the Triassic and since then tempted a shadow existence: the mammals.
