It is particularly common to listen to voices – voices that command, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also rare.
The affected person can no longer separate the important from the unimportant, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like the dream, psychosis also opens the locks to a flood of ideas and fantasies that originate from deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, senior physician at the Department of General Psychiatry at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is located in the center of the action, everything has a direct meaning to it.
At the same time, he gets into a passive role, he is, like in a dream, overwhelmed by the events and cannot actively shape them.
Schizophrenics therefore often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
A balance of reality is usually not possible for them, the delusions are cruel reality, awakening is excluded.
Having experienced hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in the dream, Fuchs says, "but the sensual and spatial structure of reality, which is perceived in psychosis, remains basically preserved."
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based in reality, the alienation of experience takes place in the real context.
Why exactly our brain beats caprioles, researchers are still puzzled.
Exceptional states can cause any person to lose the reality reference for a short time, Fuchs says.
But not everyone will develop a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that the genes are not the alone determining factors.
Researchers assume that there are minimal brain damage in those affected.
We suspect that the neuronal maturation of the brain is disturbed at an early stage of development, due to a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, for example, explains Fuchs.
But it remains a mystery how the disorder of the neuronal system comes about, which also does not manifest for many years at first.
Environmental influences also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can be triggers for psychosis when disposition is present.
Also, hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychoses because they interfere with the transmitter system.
When our brain is running hot
The crazy thing is that psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and swallow expensive drugs to get rid of them, others spend money on drugs to get some, says Lübeck psychology professor Erich Kasten.
Whether delusions are perceived as pleasant or unpleasant is often only a matter of point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports of hallucinations and concussions for ten years, and last year he evaluated his results in the book "The Irreal World in Our Head".
Hallucinations are among the typical side effects of psychosis, but also of amazingly many other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline or depression, these often include diseases such as migraines, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer’s and cranial trauma.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions even the brain of healthy people hallucinates.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, are composed of memory contents that are usually held back.
They arise when brain areas in which sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or too little inhibited; when our brain is running hot or even when stimulation is lacking.
Drugs can trigger this condition just as much as brain damage or a psychosis.
But also travel, stress, love grief or other mental states.
In recent studies, up to a third of those surveyed reported having experienced hallucination at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005 Sarah K. is 16 years old, she lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attends high school there.
A normal girl, actually.
If it wasn’t for the pictures and voices.
During the break, it can happen that a slick boy with long, dark hair will appeal to it.
When it responds to him, the classmates look at it in surprise—no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think the shy girl is a twisted daydreamer, but Sarah K. doesn’t dream, she knows.
She is awake, she hears and sees this boy, just as she hears and sees the girl in the bench next to her.
She can even feel his presence, at least for moments.
A pleasant feeling is that she likes the boy.
Am I crazy? she asks herself sometimes.
But she knows that this boy and the other delusions are not real and disappear again.
At night, the apparitions are mostly scary
Often, the illusions are also a burden.
When she sits in the classroom, she can sometimes not follow the teaching material, because the teacher in her eyes and ears is just introducing a new classmate, while explaining mathematical equations to everyone else, both audible and visible, on the board.
At night, the apparitions are usually scary.
When she waits for sleep in her dark room, which is far too rare and far too late, she often can’t tell if she’s awake or already dreaming about the pictures she sees, the frats or the girl with the bleeding cuts on her arms and legs, in front of her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, she yells at the figures.
Parents and friends don’t tell her they think they’re crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She passed the high school last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Since she has contacted the psychologist box on the Internet, she knows exactly that she is not crazy.
Wahn is also a work of art of desperation
If someone is socially isolated or suffers from a draw, he is likely to have hallucinations after a while, Kasten says.
I suspect the brain is then underemployed and takes care of its own entertainment.
Sarah K., a single child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at the age of 13, that the man she calls Papa has not been her biological father since she can think.
Since in visual and acoustic hallucinations the same areas of the brain are active, which also process real impressions and sounds, it is difficult for those affected like Sarah K. to distinguish illusions and reality. “Every experience,” Kasten says, “is taking place in the brain, the reality forms there.
Hallucinations are also images that make the brain come into being, which is why they seem so real.”
Even nocturnal dream images value boxing as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their delusions as irrational.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to appreciate the hallucinations as a special ability.
Boundary state between dream and hallucination
Unfortunately, in our overly conscious world, imaginary experience is mostly pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the Department of Psychiatry and Psychotherapy of the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, distressing disease, but it also contains positive, creative - delusion is also a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has researched the so-called oneiroid experience form, a special form of traumatized waking consciousness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams, which the experiencer considers real and which he cannot distinguish from the waking state even afterwards.
The oneiroid state of consciousness arises in trauma- or disease-related extreme situations, for example in polyradiculitis patients who experience motor paralysis with full consciousness.
When a person is threatened by self-loss and world loss, for example, by persistent, complete inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with a separate, imaginary world that is disconnected from reality, Schmidt-Degenhard says.
A kind of boundary state between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to cope with a situation in reality, a world change takes place, but the real situation is perceived in the imagination.
An intense form of meaning and meaning in an inherently intolerable situation that enables us humans to have their own design ability, not to fall into a nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his Oneiroid experiences in his book "Heart change" as a rescue action of the soul.
He is 49 years old when his consciousness travels for days after a heart valve surgery followed by a heart transplant, while his body is condemned to motionlessness at the intensive care unit.
Claussen dives into a self-created world, visits strange times and places: he experiences himself as a bedridden, old man, aboard a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among nobles who produce drugs from blood.
Being taken by a Greek on a motorcycle in his native country, surfs with his hospital bed in the firn snow of the Alps and meets a Korean mafioso.
He goes completely into the imaginary happenings, everything is real, even later in memory.
These inner journeys are fundamentally different for Claussen from any dream.
Dream is another condition, he describes his experience.
In contrast, the memories from mental journeys after years and in incidental details are clear to me.
More clear and intense even than really experienced.
The intensity of this experience blows up the horizon of our other life experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
In the end, oneiroids, psychoses, hallucinations, and drug noise show how fragile our inner images of outer reality are in the wake.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes the psychologist Kasten, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be enriching.
