The survey of 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working women see their career opportunities in the labour market limited due to their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are big differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children, depending on whether the women work or not, and if so, what kind of profession they practice.
Those of them who do no other work outside the house, work only half a day or have no fixed employment contract, are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with permanent employment, especially in the public sector, are moving towards the establishment of a family and motherhood and therefore have fewer children.
The women in the age group between 35 and 49 with a permanent position receive their first child on average only 3.7 years after contracting, a figure that increases to 4.1 years for women with permanent positions who have taken longer to achieve this and who have only realized their contraction and the first child much later.
Moreover, the type of work also has a major impact on motherhood, albeit less than the calendar in terms of conception readiness,” explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that must be taken into account in the age of women in marriage and the first child.
According to the survey, the age at the time of marriage and the first child is all the higher, the higher the level of education.
This difference was also found in women of the same age.
