Every day, thousands of vehicles involved in an accident are hauled into the workshops, where an assessor must assess the damage caused and the cost of repair.
Not a single accident is the same and calculating the cost of parts and working hours can be a lengthy and complicated task.
The calculation of repair costs of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros per hand, including parts and working hours, can take up to two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the support of the latest computer science tools, it is a matter of minutes
That’s why almost 100% of reviewers use this type of system.
The service and application providers for the assessment of accidents and repair collect the information they receive from the manufacturers in order to process it and offer it to their customers in the form of a useful program.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the American group Solera, is the market leader; 80% of all reviews are produced with their products.
The other two companies competing with the tool market for reviewing and drafting a report are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data that the manufacturers provide is anything but easy.
According to Eduardo Vel<0xC3><0xA1>zquez, sales manager of Audatex, 63 manufacturers and importers work together, each of them providing the information in a different format.
Moreover, the amount of data to be processed is getting bigger and bigger, up to the point that in the last five years even more versions, variants and motorizations have come onto the market than in the entire fifteen years before.
As soon as a new car comes onto the market, the work begins for the companies.
It is a laborious task, because each one of the thousands of vehicle parts has to be catagolized and its price entered.
In addition, each model creates an "intelligent" graphic image on which you can "click" different parts of the vehicle.
If this is a much sold model, the work can be completed in one week, if the procedure progresses quickly.
If this is a less common car, it can take up to three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information on 99.2% of cars sold in Spain.
Among the more exclusive models, they have, for example, information about the Porsche models, but not about Ferrari or Lamborghini.
With regard to the vehicle park on the roads, it is more than 99%.
Audatex has eight centers worldwide (Spain, France, Germany, USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) for the purpose of carrying out documentation work and the production of databases, and each of them specializes in specific brands.
The national headquarters are located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanics professionals) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Every year, Audatex invests 90 million euros in the development of these databases.
Every month, they record 2.5 million data and their customers receive updates every other day.
The development of this enormous flow of information allows companies to use it in different ways and thus offer different products.
The most common use is the use for repairs and repairs, but depending on the country, there are also tools for the management of scrap parts or for calculating the error or residual value of a car.
